00:00:05.628 --> 00:00:07.090
SPEAKER 1: Welcome, everybody.

00:00:07.090 --> 00:00:13.408
I'm excited today to introduce
Stand.earth and Todd Paglia.

00:00:13.408 --> 00:00:16.180
In tech industry,
we have this notion

00:00:16.180 --> 00:00:19.030
of the frenemy,
two companies that

00:00:19.030 --> 00:00:22.060
compete in one area and
partner in another area.

00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:25.090
And Stand.earth has
taken that approach

00:00:25.090 --> 00:00:30.250
to environmental activism.

00:00:30.250 --> 00:00:34.180
And their approach is to say,
we'll help companies clean up

00:00:34.180 --> 00:00:37.510
their act, and act
responsibly with respect

00:00:37.510 --> 00:00:40.670
to the environment, show
them how to do that.

00:00:40.670 --> 00:00:44.200
But if they don't, then we'll
bring the righteous wrath

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:47.470
of the public down upon them.

00:00:47.470 --> 00:00:49.060
And I think this is
a great approach,

00:00:49.060 --> 00:00:53.040
and it's proven to
be very successful.

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:57.160
Stand's had great success in
transforming the paper industry

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:02.440
to use forests more
responsibly and in saving

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:03.560
the great rainforest.

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:05.860
We saw some of the
pictures up there

00:01:05.860 --> 00:01:09.220
from when I got a chance
to accompany them up

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:11.470
to British Columbia.

00:01:11.470 --> 00:01:15.340
And let's let Todd tell you
all about it and about some

00:01:15.340 --> 00:01:20.140
of the opportunities where
we can help in this mission

00:01:20.140 --> 00:01:21.880
by bringing some
of the technologies

00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:24.900
that we have in mapping,
and satellites, and so on.

00:01:24.900 --> 00:01:26.550
Todd, welcome to Google.

00:01:26.550 --> 00:01:30.050
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:30.550 --> 00:01:33.050
TODD PAGLIA: Thanks so
much for being here today.

00:01:33.050 --> 00:01:36.740
I want to take you back to the
founding of Stand.earth, which

00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:40.640
was in the mid-1990s about
1,000 miles north of here

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:42.840
on the west coast of Canada.

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:46.460
There was a line being
drawn in the sand in a place

00:01:46.460 --> 00:01:47.600
called Clayoquot Sound.

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:50.840
The small town of Tofino
is in Clayoquot Sound.

00:01:50.840 --> 00:01:52.820
It was the last old
growth rainforest

00:01:52.820 --> 00:01:56.750
valley on the west coast
of Vancouver Island,

00:01:56.750 --> 00:01:59.750
and people had had enough.

00:01:59.750 --> 00:02:04.610
They began organizing to try to
stop the logging of this area.

00:02:04.610 --> 00:02:10.160
And it's a rainforest valley
of just incredible beauty.

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:15.260
1,000 year old Western red
cedar trees, Doug firs,

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:19.070
trees so big that 10
people linked arm to arm

00:02:19.070 --> 00:02:22.070
could barely wrap their
arms around the trunks

00:02:22.070 --> 00:02:24.140
of these trees, and
they're being cut down

00:02:24.140 --> 00:02:29.660
to make toilet paper,
newsprint, two-by-fours,

00:02:29.660 --> 00:02:31.440
and other products.

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:35.930
So the organizers started
what was a very small effort

00:02:35.930 --> 00:02:37.880
in the beginning, and
little by little, gained

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:40.640
momentum, getting people
out to this remote area

00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:42.500
to actually put their
bodies on the line

00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:44.910
to try to stop the bulldozers
and the logging trucks

00:02:44.910 --> 00:02:46.220
from coming in.

00:02:46.220 --> 00:02:49.020
And this, for whatever reason--

00:02:49.020 --> 00:02:53.240
it was partly the time, partly
so much had been lost already,

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:54.510
people responded.

00:02:54.510 --> 00:02:55.880
It struck a nerve.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:59.060
And hundreds of
people showed up.

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:02.510
And little by little,
thousands of people showed up.

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:06.170
And they began
organizing protests

00:03:06.170 --> 00:03:08.570
to try to stop the logging.

00:03:08.570 --> 00:03:09.890
The media followed.

00:03:09.890 --> 00:03:12.450
It became known as
the War in the Woods.

00:03:12.450 --> 00:03:13.850
It went on for months.

00:03:13.850 --> 00:03:15.710
And celebrities
started showing up,

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:17.750
and rock stars, and
everybody wanted

00:03:17.750 --> 00:03:20.930
to come, and get arrested,
and stand on the line

00:03:20.930 --> 00:03:24.890
with the protesters protecting
this old growth river valley.

00:03:24.890 --> 00:03:29.150
And it culminated with an
international media storm.

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:34.580
1,000 arrests, the
biggest civil disobedience

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:38.820
in Canadian history,
and it didn't work.

00:03:38.820 --> 00:03:40.460
It wasn't enough.

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:42.560
And it was from that--

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:44.900
exceeding all expectations,
every goal they

00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:48.380
set as far as turnout,
media, everything they did

00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:50.720
went way beyond their
goals, and they still

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:51.790
didn't stop the logging.

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:53.690
MacMillan Bloedel,
the logging company,

00:03:53.690 --> 00:03:55.690
just kept moving right along.

00:03:55.690 --> 00:03:58.580
And it was from that sort
of moment of desperation

00:03:58.580 --> 00:04:03.800
that the founders of
Stand.earth decided

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:06.860
to think about who
was buying this stuff.

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:09.080
So something's driving
what's happening.

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:12.920
So they took a
very basic approach

00:04:12.920 --> 00:04:15.710
and went out to the marketplace
with hundreds of letters

00:04:15.710 --> 00:04:19.250
to any company they thought
might somehow be connected

00:04:19.250 --> 00:04:21.560
to the logging in Clayoquot
Sound and the broader

00:04:21.560 --> 00:04:24.110
logging on the coast
of British Columbia,

00:04:24.110 --> 00:04:26.120
and companies were concerned.

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:28.970
They didn't realize that
their purchasing dollars were

00:04:28.970 --> 00:04:30.830
destroying this rainforest.

00:04:30.830 --> 00:04:34.290
And for the first time in
British Columbia-- and logging

00:04:34.290 --> 00:04:37.370
was king in British Columbia
and had been for decades--

00:04:37.370 --> 00:04:41.270
for the first time, the logging
company was on its heels.

00:04:41.270 --> 00:04:42.830
The logging stopped.

00:04:42.830 --> 00:04:46.640
They started having to answer
questions to their customers.

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:49.670
They started having to
work to keep contracts.

00:04:49.670 --> 00:04:52.094
They started to lose
some contracts, companies

00:04:52.094 --> 00:04:53.510
not wanting to be
part of what was

00:04:53.510 --> 00:04:56.284
happening in Clayoquot Sound.

00:04:56.284 --> 00:04:58.700
And that was the first time
that the companies were really

00:04:58.700 --> 00:05:00.200
put on the defensive.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:04.850
And the trees Clayoquot
Sound, the old growth forest

00:05:04.850 --> 00:05:06.950
of Clayoquot Sound
are still standing

00:05:06.950 --> 00:05:10.160
to this day because
of that effort

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:13.340
at the tail end of
years of protest

00:05:13.340 --> 00:05:15.530
to bring some transparency.

00:05:15.530 --> 00:05:18.740
And I think it was this
little glimpse of transparency

00:05:18.740 --> 00:05:24.320
of a tree in a forest being cut,
five or six different mills,

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:28.550
way stations, middlemen
to big-branded companies

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:29.475
at the other end.

00:05:29.475 --> 00:05:31.850
And it was just a little bit
of a glimpse of transparency

00:05:31.850 --> 00:05:34.770
that changed the
entire equation.

00:05:34.770 --> 00:05:37.280
So we took that lesson
of Clayoquot Sound

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:40.790
and started thinking, so,
how do we build campaigns

00:05:40.790 --> 00:05:45.560
from the front end that, yes,
use communications, organizing,

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:48.740
protests, all the
traditional tools,

00:05:48.740 --> 00:05:53.090
but also start to bring some
transparency to the issues

00:05:53.090 --> 00:05:53.990
we are taking on?

00:05:53.990 --> 00:05:57.440
So from one old growth
rainforest valley,

00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:00.860
we decided to try to protect a
hundred old growth rainforest

00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:05.930
valleys in an area known at
that time as the Midcoast Timber

00:06:05.930 --> 00:06:10.280
Supply area, quite
a catchy name.

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:13.679
The first piece of business for
the groups working on this--

00:06:13.679 --> 00:06:15.470
and there were a lot
of other organizations

00:06:15.470 --> 00:06:19.730
beyond Stand, including NRDC,
and Greenpeace, and Rainforest

00:06:19.730 --> 00:06:22.010
Action Network, and many others.

00:06:22.010 --> 00:06:25.250
The first piece of
business was to rename it.

00:06:25.250 --> 00:06:28.190
We retained the
Great Bear Rainforest

00:06:28.190 --> 00:06:33.440
after the spirit bear, which is
the iconic symbol of the Great

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:34.530
Bear Rainforest.

00:06:34.530 --> 00:06:37.640
It's the only place in the
world where 1 out of every 10

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:40.310
black bears is born white.

00:06:40.310 --> 00:06:41.360
They're not albinos.

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:43.010
They're not polar bears.

00:06:43.010 --> 00:06:47.400
They're actually a white bear
known as the spirit bear,

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:50.400
and revered by the
First Nations who

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:53.860
have lived in this landscape
for thousands of years.

00:06:53.860 --> 00:06:57.780
And we started building into
the campaign transparency,

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:03.150
trying to track from this very
remote area wood, paper, pulp,

00:07:03.150 --> 00:07:05.160
all the way through
the entire system

00:07:05.160 --> 00:07:07.410
to big-branded companies.

00:07:07.410 --> 00:07:13.200
So now, we had 100 valleys,
3 companies, and literally

00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:15.780
thousands of big-branded
companies buying the product

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:17.280
at the end of the
line, and they had

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:18.820
no idea they were doing that.

00:07:18.820 --> 00:07:23.070
So it was a major private
eye investigation effort

00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:26.430
to figure out where all this
stuff went to and then to begin

00:07:26.430 --> 00:07:27.810
educating the companies.

00:07:27.810 --> 00:07:31.020
Our methods got a little
bit better at that point.

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:33.240
We went from just sending
a scattershot letter

00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:37.540
to hundreds of companies to
actually tracking the wood,

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:40.500
paper, and pulp using a bunch
of different methods, some

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:42.600
of which meant just
going to mill towns,

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:45.060
and hanging out in the
bar, and figuring out

00:07:45.060 --> 00:07:47.100
where the customers were.

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:48.984
So folks at the
bar would say, hey,

00:07:48.984 --> 00:07:50.650
we just got a big
order from Home Depot.

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:54.180
We just got a bigger
order from Staples.

00:07:54.180 --> 00:07:55.560
We also ended up using--

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:58.890
anybody remember the
LoJack car device?

00:07:58.890 --> 00:08:02.130
So we would use the LoJack which
would track your stolen car.

00:08:02.130 --> 00:08:06.300
So we would track
our stolen forests

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:10.980
and use that sort of device
to track from especially rail

00:08:10.980 --> 00:08:14.520
shipments all the way to
the big-branded companies.

00:08:14.520 --> 00:08:16.470
And little by little,
we chipped away

00:08:16.470 --> 00:08:19.512
at the transparency
problem we were having.

00:08:19.512 --> 00:08:21.720
And a lot of companies, just
like in Clayoquot Sound,

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:25.830
didn't want to be part of
destroying a rainforest.

00:08:25.830 --> 00:08:28.320
Over time, it became
millions of dollars

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:31.044
of contracts put online
to tens of millions

00:08:31.044 --> 00:08:32.460
to hundreds of
millions of dollars

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:34.950
of contracts put on the line.

00:08:34.950 --> 00:08:38.400
And using that power, we
were able to bring industry

00:08:38.400 --> 00:08:39.659
to the table.

00:08:39.659 --> 00:08:44.110
At the same time, First
Nations on the coast of DC,

00:08:44.110 --> 00:08:46.390
for the first time
in a long time,

00:08:46.390 --> 00:08:50.640
got organized in a way that
went beyond individual First

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:51.720
Nations.

00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:55.770
They became a collective known
as the Coastal First Nations

00:08:55.770 --> 00:08:56.730
in British Columbia.

00:08:56.730 --> 00:08:58.380
They have not signed treaties.

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:02.610
So they have actual a somewhat
undefined but very powerful

00:09:02.610 --> 00:09:03.630
right to title.

00:09:03.630 --> 00:09:06.360
And so they became a
political force of their own

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:09.760
while we were driving the
marketplace towards change.

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:12.540
And through a series
of negotiations,

00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:16.260
we went from the starting point,
which you can barely see here

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:20.140
on the screen, but almost no
protection in the Great Bear

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:22.830
to a third of it
being protected.

00:09:22.830 --> 00:09:25.020
2005, we got to round 50--

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:25.620
no.

00:09:25.620 --> 00:09:27.680
2009, we got to 50%.

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:32.190
2015, we put the final
details into place

00:09:32.190 --> 00:09:35.970
to get over 80% of the Great
Bear Rainforest protected,

00:09:35.970 --> 00:09:37.590
off limits to logging.

00:09:37.590 --> 00:09:42.570
And we created fiber flow
processes for the logging

00:09:42.570 --> 00:09:45.720
companies to have a
lower impact but be

00:09:45.720 --> 00:09:47.620
able to maintain
their businesses.

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:48.810
So it was a real win-win.

00:09:48.810 --> 00:09:51.690
And what we found is once First
Nations, environmental groups,

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:55.020
and industry were on the same
page with a very detailed plan,

00:09:55.020 --> 00:09:57.660
the government was more than
happy to move forward and move

00:09:57.660 --> 00:09:59.640
that into permanent legislation.

00:09:59.640 --> 00:10:02.730
So using these methods of
really increasing and building

00:10:02.730 --> 00:10:05.670
transparency into
our campaigns, we've

00:10:05.670 --> 00:10:09.030
been able to move around 60
million acres of old growth

00:10:09.030 --> 00:10:11.850
and endangered forest towards
protection over the last 2

00:10:11.850 --> 00:10:13.560
decades.

00:10:13.560 --> 00:10:18.150
And we then started
getting pulled increasingly

00:10:18.150 --> 00:10:20.100
into climate change.

00:10:20.100 --> 00:10:22.950
One of the first issues
that we had to address,

00:10:22.950 --> 00:10:27.210
in the middle of this map,
there was a pipeline proposal

00:10:27.210 --> 00:10:30.240
by the Enbridge Corporation
to bring a giant tar sands

00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:31.500
pipeline.

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:33.960
Right at the point
when we were going over

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:37.170
50% of the Great Bear
protected, heading towards 80,

00:10:37.170 --> 00:10:40.260
they thought it would be a great
time to bring a giant pipeline

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:42.360
right into the Great
Bear Rainforest,

00:10:42.360 --> 00:10:45.920
bringing hundreds of tankers
into the Great Bear Sea.

00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:49.290
This was a fight that
went on for the better

00:10:49.290 --> 00:10:51.210
part of a decade.

00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:54.720
We were able largely through
leadership of First Nations

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:57.540
groups to beat
that pipeline back,

00:10:57.540 --> 00:10:59.250
tremendous organizing
on the ground.

00:10:59.250 --> 00:11:02.950
And this movement of people
all around North America

00:11:02.950 --> 00:11:05.700
and beyond fighting
oil infrastructure

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:06.856
has had incredible success.

00:11:06.856 --> 00:11:08.730
You've all heard about
the Keystone Pipeline,

00:11:08.730 --> 00:11:11.260
which has been beaten a
couple of times by now.

00:11:11.260 --> 00:11:13.226
The Enbridge pipeline,
we're in the midst

00:11:13.226 --> 00:11:15.600
of the fight of our lives with
the Kinder Morgan pipeline

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:19.370
coming into Vancouver on
the port of Vancouver.

00:11:19.370 --> 00:11:21.990
We're hopefully going to
be able to turn that back.

00:11:21.990 --> 00:11:25.310
But as we as a movement
succeeded on pipelines,

00:11:25.310 --> 00:11:27.850
the oil companies
developed a plan B.

00:11:27.850 --> 00:11:30.701
The plan B was oil trains.

00:11:30.701 --> 00:11:32.700
So if they couldn't get
their pipelines through,

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:36.330
and they were getting delays
and defeats on pipelines,

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:38.910
they thought they might be able
to start moving oil by rail,

00:11:38.910 --> 00:11:41.730
and this took
everybody by surprise.

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:45.210
This was something
that heretofore, oil

00:11:45.210 --> 00:11:50.220
would occasionally go on rail,
but not very often and not

00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:51.780
in any quantity that mattered.

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:54.390
And suddenly, you were
getting about five years ago,

00:11:54.390 --> 00:11:57.600
thousands of percent
increase every single year.

00:11:57.600 --> 00:12:00.930
And suddenly, there were
more than two dozen oil

00:12:00.930 --> 00:12:04.410
by rail terminals, new
terminals being sighted

00:12:04.410 --> 00:12:06.600
all across North America.

00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:09.330
So what we did is we were
far too small to take on

00:12:09.330 --> 00:12:10.800
this challenge ourselves.

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:13.980
We started partnering with
Frontline Communities,

00:12:13.980 --> 00:12:17.610
developed a network,
Crude Awakening Network,

00:12:17.610 --> 00:12:21.150
which is 275 group strong
at this moment, everything

00:12:21.150 --> 00:12:23.910
from a couple of people
working at the kitchen table

00:12:23.910 --> 00:12:27.240
to the Sierra Club and Natural
Resources Defense Council.

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:29.100
Banding together, we
were able to begin

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:30.510
to push back on this threat.

00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:32.490
And one of the key
components, though,

00:12:32.490 --> 00:12:36.000
was getting back to the
issue of transparency.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.940
We created a tool called
The Blast-Zone.org.

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:40.860
And this is a map.

00:12:40.860 --> 00:12:44.900
We're somewhere over in here
outside of the blast zone.

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:48.390
As more and more oil by
rail was being shipped,

00:12:48.390 --> 00:12:51.750
the trains had a tendency to
explode more and more often.

00:12:51.750 --> 00:12:54.180
Usually because a
lot of the rails

00:12:54.180 --> 00:12:59.850
are in somewhat isolated areas,
there were not a lot of deaths.

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:00.930
Thank god.

00:13:00.930 --> 00:13:02.590
But in some places, there were.

00:13:02.590 --> 00:13:06.540
In Lac-Megantic,
Quebec, 47 people

00:13:06.540 --> 00:13:09.150
lost their lives in an
oil train explosion.

00:13:09.150 --> 00:13:11.130
We had a number of
very close calls

00:13:11.130 --> 00:13:14.310
with, for example, an
oil train turning over

00:13:14.310 --> 00:13:17.040
in a tunnel in Seattle
during the summer.

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:18.150
It didn't ignite.

00:13:18.150 --> 00:13:19.770
But there were so
many close calls

00:13:19.770 --> 00:13:21.750
and so many communities
were up in arms

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:26.007
and trying to fight this
that we created this tool.

00:13:26.007 --> 00:13:27.840
And it was really kind
of the next iteration

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:29.280
of transparency for us.

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:30.780
This wasn't just
information we were

00:13:30.780 --> 00:13:32.257
trying to get for ourselves.

00:13:32.257 --> 00:13:33.840
It was information
that we were trying

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:35.940
to get, and then sort
of unleash it, and see

00:13:35.940 --> 00:13:37.399
what people did with it.

00:13:37.399 --> 00:13:39.690
So you can put in any address
anywhere in North America

00:13:39.690 --> 00:13:43.200
and find out how far you were
from the blast zone, which

00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:47.430
is the federally-defined area
where you can see from red,

00:13:47.430 --> 00:13:50.100
this is basically almost
sort of an incineration

00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:52.450
zone to an evacuation zone.

00:13:52.450 --> 00:13:54.720
You don't want to be
near any one of those.

00:13:54.720 --> 00:13:57.180
And they go right through
many of our cities and towns.

00:13:57.180 --> 00:14:00.650
So this was an incredible
mobilizing tool.

00:14:00.650 --> 00:14:05.530
We were able to allow groups all
over North America to use it.

00:14:05.530 --> 00:14:07.290
And they got the
attention of the mayor

00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:09.780
when the mayor's house
was in the blast zone,

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:12.240
the city councilor's house
was in the blast zone,

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:15.640
when their schoolchildren, when
the school was in the blast

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:16.140
zone.

00:14:16.140 --> 00:14:19.140
And it also led to a number
of reports that had never

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:23.640
been possible before,
including many of the areas

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:26.160
that we were working
on, like this picture

00:14:26.160 --> 00:14:28.680
here, were in very
low-income areas.

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:30.360
And so we were able
to actually use

00:14:30.360 --> 00:14:33.990
demographic data, partnering
with environmental justice

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:38.340
groups, to show some of the
new terminals who was at risk.

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:41.250
In many of these
places, it was 80%, 90%

00:14:41.250 --> 00:14:43.500
and higher low-income
communities

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:45.150
and communities of color.

00:14:45.150 --> 00:14:48.510
This also became a huge rallying
point for these communities

00:14:48.510 --> 00:14:53.370
to push their elected leaders to
reject the oil train terminals.

00:14:53.370 --> 00:14:56.990
And over the course
of a few years,

00:14:56.990 --> 00:15:02.770
we were able, with this network,
to beat over 20 oil train

00:15:02.770 --> 00:15:05.710
terminals and really
answer a threat that

00:15:05.710 --> 00:15:11.220
was popping up everywhere in
an incredibly effective way.

00:15:11.220 --> 00:15:14.260
And a lot of it really came
down to transparency and access

00:15:14.260 --> 00:15:17.050
to the information.

00:15:17.050 --> 00:15:20.364
The Blast-Zone has been one
of the best tools we've ever

00:15:20.364 --> 00:15:22.030
come up with, and
it's the kind of thing

00:15:22.030 --> 00:15:25.390
that is really way out
there for groups like us.

00:15:25.390 --> 00:15:27.094
It is an outlier,
and it's something

00:15:27.094 --> 00:15:29.260
that we actually need to
see a lot more of, I think,

00:15:29.260 --> 00:15:31.020
in the future.

00:15:31.020 --> 00:15:35.620
Our work on climate change has
gone from oil infrastructure

00:15:35.620 --> 00:15:39.260
now more and more into
changing industries.

00:15:39.260 --> 00:15:42.580
We have a new campaign actually
launched as of this morning

00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:44.660
on the fashion industry.

00:15:44.660 --> 00:15:49.660
The fashion industry itself is
the fifth largest contributor

00:15:49.660 --> 00:15:51.550
to climate change,
if it were a nation.

00:15:51.550 --> 00:15:56.230
So that's about 5 and 1/2% of
total greenhouse gas emissions.

00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:58.630
And again, like we've
learned over time,

00:15:58.630 --> 00:16:01.360
we're trying to build
more and more transparency

00:16:01.360 --> 00:16:02.320
into this system.

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:05.350
And there's a new
fledgling effort

00:16:05.350 --> 00:16:08.140
by a couple of our
allies, IPE, which

00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:12.310
is a group run by Ma Jun, the
Goldman Environmental Prize

00:16:12.310 --> 00:16:15.010
winner, and NRDC is
partnering with this effort

00:16:15.010 --> 00:16:21.990
as well, for the first time
to map factories in China

00:16:21.990 --> 00:16:24.210
and the brands
associated with them.

00:16:24.210 --> 00:16:27.300
So you'll see Puma,
New Balance, Target.

00:16:27.300 --> 00:16:28.670
And this is a voluntary effort--

00:16:28.670 --> 00:16:30.360
Esprit is also part
of this effort--

00:16:30.360 --> 00:16:33.090
it's a voluntary
effort to begin to show

00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:36.000
where they're making
the shoes and apparel

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.780
that they manufacture.

00:16:38.780 --> 00:16:43.700
And this is paired with
real-time pollution monitoring

00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:44.490
data.

00:16:44.490 --> 00:16:50.390
So any lack of compliance
is going to be known,

00:16:50.390 --> 00:16:53.420
and local people on the
ground can access this

00:16:53.420 --> 00:16:56.640
and actually go to the factories
and see what's happening.

00:16:56.640 --> 00:17:00.380
And the photographic
and other information

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:03.800
you can get when a mill
is out of compliance

00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:06.380
will lead directly
to a complaint

00:17:06.380 --> 00:17:09.140
to the company that is
the ultimate buyer of what

00:17:09.140 --> 00:17:10.099
that factory makes.

00:17:10.099 --> 00:17:13.490
And I think this is the very
beginning of what's going

00:17:13.490 --> 00:17:15.049
to change the apparel sector.

00:17:17.780 --> 00:17:20.240
Our part of this is we
launched our campaign actually

00:17:20.240 --> 00:17:24.890
a few hours ago at
Levi's in San Francisco,

00:17:24.890 --> 00:17:28.460
the iconic California
jeans company,

00:17:28.460 --> 00:17:31.820
and we are encouraging them to
get on the pathway to Paris.

00:17:31.820 --> 00:17:35.360
I think part of how they are
going to be part of the broader

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:39.440
campaign is to set a real
goal to reduce their climate

00:17:39.440 --> 00:17:40.580
impacts.

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:43.700
This campaign is well timed
because it's very possible.

00:17:43.700 --> 00:17:45.837
In fact, they have a
mill that waterless.

00:17:45.837 --> 00:17:47.670
They can be running
their mills not on coal,

00:17:47.670 --> 00:17:49.550
but on alternative energy.

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:51.470
And this is an
effort that we think

00:17:51.470 --> 00:17:56.420
will drive companies to produce
real long-term commitments

00:17:56.420 --> 00:17:59.090
and begin mapping
their supply chains.

00:17:59.090 --> 00:18:01.140
They're incredibly complex.

00:18:01.140 --> 00:18:03.860
And there's no way they
or officials in China

00:18:03.860 --> 00:18:07.670
can possibly monitor it and
keep tabs on whether or not

00:18:07.670 --> 00:18:09.890
they're in compliance,
but this network

00:18:09.890 --> 00:18:13.850
of groups working on climate
issues and local pollution

00:18:13.850 --> 00:18:14.810
issues can.

00:18:14.810 --> 00:18:19.990
So I think this is really a
whole new world when we're

00:18:19.990 --> 00:18:25.360
looking at what's possible
for mapping and giving access

00:18:25.360 --> 00:18:28.630
to ordinary citizens, let's
say nothing of local government

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:30.460
officials, about
what's happening

00:18:30.460 --> 00:18:34.120
in their homes, their towns, and
cities that might impact them.

00:18:34.120 --> 00:18:36.490
And so over time, over
the last two decades,

00:18:36.490 --> 00:18:38.420
I think that there
is this trend--

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:43.710
this is a very
imperfect calculation,

00:18:43.710 --> 00:18:47.820
the kind only a liberal arts
major would come up with.

00:18:47.820 --> 00:18:49.610
But I really think
that our work has

00:18:49.610 --> 00:18:51.200
shown over the last
couple of decades

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:54.890
that transparency plus
strategy equals change.

00:18:54.890 --> 00:19:02.900
And people like me who are
lawyers, campaign strategists,

00:19:02.900 --> 00:19:04.791
media people,
that's most of what

00:19:04.791 --> 00:19:06.290
the environmental
movement is about,

00:19:06.290 --> 00:19:08.930
