00:36:51.520 --> 00:36:53.530
hire all sorts of
different groups

00:36:53.530 --> 00:36:55.210
of post-military refugee.

00:36:55.210 --> 00:36:57.950
Like, they're great, but
they're terrible on this issue.

00:36:57.950 --> 00:37:00.550
And there's got to be a way
to tell this story that's

00:37:00.550 --> 00:37:04.050
empowering and not, like,
oh, another bad thing,

00:37:04.050 --> 00:37:05.690
because they're going to change.

00:37:05.690 --> 00:37:06.650
It's going to take
us a little while,

00:37:06.650 --> 00:37:07.210
but they're going to change.

00:37:07.210 --> 00:37:09.070
But it's exactly, I
think, the kind of thing

00:37:09.070 --> 00:37:11.120
that we need to tell
in a better way.

00:37:11.120 --> 00:37:15.180
So tell me how to
tell that story.

00:37:15.180 --> 00:37:17.010
AUDIENCE: Thanks for
the interesting talk.

00:37:17.010 --> 00:37:19.380
So in the spirit of what
previous questioners have done,

00:37:19.380 --> 00:37:20.796
I'll start with
my qualifications.

00:37:20.796 --> 00:37:23.074
I was camped at the Black
Hole in the summer of '93.

00:37:23.074 --> 00:37:24.240
You'll know what that means.

00:37:24.240 --> 00:37:26.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:26.310 --> 00:37:28.680
But my question is
about transparency,

00:37:28.680 --> 00:37:31.110
and I'm wondering what the
obstacles have been to that.

00:37:31.110 --> 00:37:33.276
For example, I would think
a forest company wouldn't

00:37:33.276 --> 00:37:36.240
want its competitors knowing
who its clients were,

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:41.190
or an apparel
company's competitors

00:37:41.190 --> 00:37:45.195
knowing who its suppliers were.

00:37:45.195 --> 00:37:48.086
TODD PAGLIA: Transparency
is always impossible.

00:37:48.086 --> 00:37:50.850
AUDIENCE: What obstacles
have you run into with that,

00:37:50.850 --> 00:37:52.075
and what can we do about it?

00:37:52.075 --> 00:37:52.825
TODD PAGLIA: Yeah.

00:37:52.825 --> 00:37:57.590
We started tracking or trying
to track extreme oil, so

00:37:57.590 --> 00:38:00.020
oil from the tar sands.

00:38:00.020 --> 00:38:05.270
And we were told by our
allies, funders, and companies,

00:38:05.270 --> 00:38:06.350
you cannot track it.

00:38:06.350 --> 00:38:08.150
Like, it was not possible.

00:38:08.150 --> 00:38:11.990
Not only do they not
want it to be tracked.

00:38:11.990 --> 00:38:15.017
They didn't think it
was possible to track.

00:38:15.017 --> 00:38:16.850
But if you think about
it, it's a little bit

00:38:16.850 --> 00:38:20.000
like pulp and paper, which they
also said it was impossible.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:21.290
But it's all connected.

00:38:21.290 --> 00:38:23.840
Like, with oil,
it's even easier.

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:24.530
It's a pipe.

00:38:24.530 --> 00:38:27.410
Like, it's a pipe from one
place to a refinery, and a pipe

00:38:27.410 --> 00:38:30.930
from there to somewhere else,
and then eventually to trucks.

00:38:30.930 --> 00:38:34.700
So we started going about
mapping it not the way

00:38:34.700 --> 00:38:38.030
you folks map it, but very
sort of, like, notebooks,

00:38:38.030 --> 00:38:43.070
and tracking a truck that left
a certain refinery that we knew

00:38:43.070 --> 00:38:47.180
had tar sands, following
it to a refueling station,

00:38:47.180 --> 00:38:50.840
and then seeing corporate
semis come in and refuel there,

00:38:50.840 --> 00:38:53.540
thus linking them
to the tar sands.

00:38:53.540 --> 00:38:54.710
And so we did that.

00:38:54.710 --> 00:38:57.650
And eventually, we got
all these companies

00:38:57.650 --> 00:39:03.740
to agree to get off of using tar
sands oil to fuel their fleets.

00:39:03.740 --> 00:39:06.410
They didn't like it
because they don't

00:39:06.410 --> 00:39:08.090
want a lot of transparency.

00:39:08.090 --> 00:39:12.090
It results in a lack of control.

00:39:12.090 --> 00:39:15.150
And the whole idea that
everything is a trade secret

00:39:15.150 --> 00:39:17.510
is insane, and that's
what they usually

00:39:17.510 --> 00:39:20.220
trot out in one way or another.

00:39:20.220 --> 00:39:22.160
But what we've seen
over the last 20 years

00:39:22.160 --> 00:39:25.990
is once transparency is
sort of forced upon them,

00:39:25.990 --> 00:39:28.720
that they operate just fine.

00:39:28.720 --> 00:39:31.360
Everything from pulp paper to
two-by-fours, like, yes, there

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:35.260
are some things that are actual
trade secrets 99% of what they

00:39:35.260 --> 00:39:37.440
say are trade secrets are not.

00:39:37.440 --> 00:39:39.730
And so we're willing
to carve out that 1%.

00:39:39.730 --> 00:39:40.510
Fine.

00:39:40.510 --> 00:39:42.100
You can keep that secret.

00:39:42.100 --> 00:39:46.540
But the world, I think, is
going in this direction,

00:39:46.540 --> 00:39:48.190
and Google is one
of the drivers.

00:39:48.190 --> 00:39:49.750
And I think that
companies that are

00:39:49.750 --> 00:39:52.210
going to succeed in
the next decade-plus

00:39:52.210 --> 00:39:54.020
are going to be able
to deal with it.

00:39:54.020 --> 00:39:56.650
And those that can't are
going to suffer, I think,

00:39:56.650 --> 00:39:58.541
in the marketplace.

00:39:58.541 --> 00:40:00.040
And it's not something
they're going

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:02.950
to like or be comfortable with,
but it's happening anyway.

00:40:02.950 --> 00:40:06.280
And every industry that we've
seen that we've worked with

00:40:06.280 --> 00:40:09.410
has said it's impossible and
then was able to deal with it.

00:40:09.410 --> 00:40:12.697
So I think it's more
myth than anything else.

00:40:12.697 --> 00:40:13.530
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:40:13.530 --> 00:40:15.210
Well, thank you, Mr. Paglia.

00:40:15.210 --> 00:40:17.390
Thank you, everyone, for coming.

